Motivating Philosophies

Mathematics Master of Arts (MA): “App States Master of Arts in Mathematics is designed to prepare you to teach mathematics and impart its importance to the next generation.”

This preparation also includes introductory statistics, which is commonly taught at community colleges.

From the 2025 revision to the American Statistical Associations GAISE College Report

“Introductory statistics courses serve as students first formal encounter with statistical thinking and methodology. These courses should emphasize the statistical process while building conceptual understanding that prepares students for advanced study or informed citizenship.”

GAISE Student Learning Outcomes

  1. Identify cases, variables, and types of variables in data sets, including multivariable data sets.
  2. Explain how study design affects what conclusions can be drawn from the data. In particular, explain the importance of random sampling and random assignment.
  3. Identify and interpret appropriate graphs and summary statistics in both univariate and multivariate settings.
  4. Use statistical software or apps to create visualizations, produce summary statistics, and carry out the computational aspects of statistical analysis.
  5. Articulate the role that random variation plays in statistical inference. In particular, articulate its role in generalizing from a sample to a population.

  1. Identify the key methods to use in statistical inference and interpret results from those methods.
  2. Recognize that sampling variation is one reason that conclusions drawn from statistical inference might be incorrect, and that replication and reproducibility are important to verify conclusions.
  3. Use statistical models, such as linear regression, for prediction.
  4. Recognize ethical issues and dilemmas in statistical practice.
  5. Communicate, clearly and in context, results obtained from data.

GAISE Recommendations

The following pedagogical recommendations are designed to support instructors in creating courses that enable students to achieve the GAISE student learning outcomes.

  1. Teach statistics and data science as processes of gleaning insights from data to inform evidence-based decisions.
  2. Emphasize effective written and oral communication of results from data, with attention to the scope and limitations of conclusions.
  3. Focus on conceptual understanding rather than algebraic manipulation and formulas.
  4. Integrate real data with a context and purpose throughout the course. Select data that are meaningful and engaging to the students.

  1. Encourage multivariable thinking.
  2. Incorporate software/apps to explore concepts and work with data.
  3. Emphasize responsible and ethical conduct in the collection and use of data and in their analysis.
  4. Employ evidence-based pedagogies that actively engage students in the learning process.
  5. Use a variety of formative and summative assessments to improve teaching and learning.
  6. Implement inclusive strategies that create learning environments where all students are valued.

Our primary textbook, Introduction to Modern Statistics (2e) by Mine etinkaya-Rundel and Johanna Hardin, aligns with GAISE, as do our course learning goals. See the syllabus!

Course Assessments

  • DataCamp (20%): online tutorials to teach coding/concepts
  • Homework (10%): primarily problems from the textbook
  • Data Labs (20%): applied data analysis exercises using R
  • Project (15%): group data analysis project/presentation
  • Exams (30%): take-home midterm and final exam
  • Ethics (5%): online human research ethics course

Written work typically will be completed using R Markdown, with R and LaTeX code as needed. We will use Appalachians RStudio server in class, as well as other selected technology.

Additional details are provided in the syllabus and on AsULearn.

Lets go to AsULearn and take a look!

DataCamp is a platform for learning data science and statistics. The courses present concepts and R coding using short videos and hands-on-the-keyboard exercises, with hints and feedback on each exercise. You can learn from your mistakes and revise your work until you solidify and succeed.

From the American Statistical Association: “Statistical education and training must continue to evolve”

We will use DataCamp to learn and practice some fundamental R programming and data analysis concepts. This is how I initially learned many of my R programming skills.

Access DataCamp

  • Create a DataCamp account using your Appalachian email.

  • In Account Settings, add your first/last names for the roster.

  • Join our DataCamp class using the link provided on AsULearn.

You will have six months of free access to all DataCamp content.

Git : an open-source version control and collaboration system

GitHub : web-based hosting service (hub) for version-controlled projects using Git, with some added features

If you are interested in this, I can show you how to connect it to RStudio to back up your work.

R : a free and open-source statistical programming language

R Studio : a free and open-source IDE for R, it supports projects and add-ins and has integrated support for Git and GitHub

tidyverse : “an opinionated collection of R packages designed for data science”

Active vs.Passive Learning

Be an active participant and take charge of your own learning!

Positive Practices

  • engage with digital textbooks and other course materials
  • come to class, take organized notes, actively participate
  • use office hours to get individualized attention/feedback
  • complete all of the assigned DataCamp courses
  • complete all of the assigned homework and data labs
  • collaborate with your group on your data analysis project
  • review, understand, and correct your misconceptions
  • practice both new and existing knowledge and skills
  • solidify your knowledge and make new connections
  • demonstrate your content and skill proficiency

When allowed (which is most assignments), teach and learn from your classmates.

Most real-life projects are not solo ventures; theyre accomplished via teamwork.

You wont be alone in this class unless you choose to be. Please dont do that.

Listening/reading are receptive speaking/ writing are productive.
